The key is to make `Table` generic over the row type `T` and constrain `columns` to use `keyof T` as the accessor:

```ts
interface Column<T> {
  key: keyof T;
  header: string;
  render?: (value: T[keyof T], row: T) => React.ReactNode;
}

interface TableProps<T> {
  data: T[];
  columns: Column<T>[];
}

function Table<T>({ data, columns }: TableProps<T>) {
  return (
    <table>
      <thead><tr>{columns.map(c => <th key={String(c.key)}>{c.header}</th>)}</tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        {data.map((row, i) => (
          <tr key={i}>
            {columns.map(c => (
              <td key={String(c.key)}>{c.render ? c.render(row[c.key], row) : String(row[c.key])}</td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  );
}
```

TypeScript will now infer `T` from `data` and enforce that every `column.key` is a valid property of that type.

Use a mapped/distributive trick with a helper type:

```ts
type Column<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]: {
    key: K;
    header: string;
    render?: (value: T[K], row: T) => React.ReactNode;
  };
}[keyof T];
```

This is a **distributive object type** — it creates a union of column shapes, one per key, so `render` receives the exact type for that key rather than the wide union `T[keyof T]`.

Usage stays the same:
```ts
const cols: Column<User>[] = [
  { key: 'age', header: 'Age', render: (v) => `${v} yrs` }, // v: number ✓
];
```
